32 // The abstract syntax tree is an intermediate, light-weight
33 // representation of the parsed JavaScript code suitable for
34 // compilation to native code.
35 
36 // Nodes are allocated in a separate zone, which allows faster
37 // allocation and constant-time deallocation of the entire syntax
38 // tree.

145 class AstNode: public ZoneObject {
146  public:
147 #define DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM(type) k##type,
148  enum NodeType : uint8_t {
149  AST_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM) /* , */
150  FAILURE_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM)
151  };
152 #undef DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM
153 
154  NodeType node_type() const { return NodeTypeField::decode(bit_field_); }
155  int position() const { return position_; }
156 
157 #ifdef DEBUG
158  void Print(Isolate* isolate);
159 #endif // DEBUG
160 
161  // Type testing & conversion functions overridden by concrete subclasses.
162 #define DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS(type) \
163  V8_INLINE bool Is##type() const; \
164  V8_INLINE type* As##type(); \
165  V8_INLINE const type* As##type() const;
166  AST_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS)
167  FAILURE_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS)
168 #undef DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS
169 
170  IterationStatement* AsIterationStatement();
171  MaterializedLiteral* AsMaterializedLiteral();
172 
173  private:
174  int position_;
175  using NodeTypeField = base::BitField<NodeType, 0, 6>;
176 
177  protected:
178  uint32_t bit_field_;
179 
180  template <class T, int size>
181  using NextBitField = NodeTypeField::Next<T, size>;
182 
183  AstNode(int position, NodeType type)
184  : position_(position), bit_field_(NodeTypeField::encode(type)) {}
185 };

194 class Expression : public AstNode {
195  public:
196  // True iff the expression is a valid reference expression.
197  bool IsValidReferenceExpression() const;
198 
199  // True iff the expression is a private name.
200  bool IsPrivateName() const;
201 
202  // Helpers for ToBoolean conversion.
203  bool ToBooleanIsTrue() const;
204  bool ToBooleanIsFalse() const;
205 
206  // Symbols that cannot be parsed as array indices are considered property
207  // names. We do not treat symbols that can be array indexes as property
208  // names because [] for string objects is handled only by keyed ICs.
209  bool IsPropertyName() const;
210 
211  // True iff the expression is a class or function expression without
212  // a syntactic name.
213  bool IsAnonymousFunctionDefinition() const;
214 
215  // True iff the expression is a concise method definition.
216  bool IsConciseMethodDefinition() const;
217 
218  // True iff the expression is an accessor function definition.
219  bool IsAccessorFunctionDefinition() const;
220 
221  // True iff the expression is a literal represented as a smi.
222  bool IsSmiLiteral() const;
223 
224  // True iff the expression is a literal represented as a number.
225  V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE bool IsNumberLiteral() const;
226 
227  // True iff the expression is a string literal.
228  bool IsStringLiteral() const;
229 
230  // True iff the expression is a cons string literal.
231  bool IsConsStringLiteral() const;
232 
233  // True iff the expression is the null literal.
234  bool IsNullLiteral() const;
235 
236  bool IsBooleanLiteral() const;
237 
238  // True iff the expression is the hole literal.
239  bool IsTheHoleLiteral() const;
240 
241  // True if we can prove that the expression is the undefined literal. Note
242  // that this also checks for loads of the global "undefined" variable.
243  bool IsUndefinedLiteral() const;
244 
245  // True if either null literal or undefined literal.
246  inline bool IsNullOrUndefinedLiteral() const {
247  return IsNullLiteral() || IsUndefinedLiteral();
248  }
249 
250  // True if a literal and not null or undefined.
251  bool IsLiteralButNotNullOrUndefined() const;
252 
253  bool IsCompileTimeValue();
254 
255  bool IsPattern() {
256  static_assert(kObjectLiteral + 1 == kArrayLiteral);
257  return base::IsInRange(node_type(), kObjectLiteral, kArrayLiteral);
258  }
259 
260  bool is_parenthesized() const {
261  return IsParenthesizedField::decode(bit_field_);
262  }
263 
264  void mark_parenthesized() {
265  bit_field_ = IsParenthesizedField::update(bit_field_, true);
266  }
267 
268  void clear_parenthesized() {
269  bit_field_ = IsParenthesizedField::update(bit_field_, false);
270  }
271 
272  private:
273  using IsParenthesizedField = AstNode::NextBitField<bool, 1>;
274 
275  protected:
276  Expression(int pos, NodeType type) : AstNode(pos, type) {
277  DCHECK(!is_parenthesized());
278  }
279 
280  template <class T, int size>
281  using NextBitField = IsParenthesizedField::Next<T, size>;
282 };

291 // V8's notion of BreakableStatement does not correspond to the notion of
292 // BreakableStatement in ECMAScript. In V8, the idea is that a
293 // BreakableStatement is a statement that can be the target of a break
294 // statement.
295 //
296 // Since we don't want to track a list of labels for all kinds of statements, we
297 // only declare switches, loops, and blocks as BreakableStatements. This means
298 // that we implement breaks targeting other statement forms as breaks targeting
299 // a substatement thereof. For instance, in "foo: if (b) { f(); break foo; }" we
300 // pretend that foo is the label of the inner block. That's okay because one
301 // can't observe the difference.
302 // TODO(verwaest): Reconsider this optimization now that the tracking of labels
303 // is done at runtime.
304 class BreakableStatement : public Statement {
305  protected:
306  BreakableStatement(int position, NodeType type) : Statement(position, type) {}
307 };
308 
309 class Block final : public BreakableStatement {
310  public:
311  ZonePtrList<Statement>* statements() { return &statements_; }
312  bool ignore_completion_value() const {
313  return IgnoreCompletionField::decode(bit_field_);
314  }
315  bool is_breakable() const { return IsBreakableField::decode(bit_field_); }
316  bool is_initialization_block_for_parameters() const {
317  return IsInitializationBlockForParametersField::decode(bit_field_);
318  }
319 
320  Scope* scope() const { return scope_; }
321  void set_scope(Scope* scope) { scope_ = scope; }
322 
323  void InitializeStatements(const ScopedPtrList<Statement>& statements,
324  Zone* zone) {
325  DCHECK_EQ(0, statements_.length());
326  statements_ = ZonePtrList<Statement>(statements.ToConstVector(), zone);
327  }
328 
329  private:
330  friend class AstNodeFactory;
331  friend Zone;
332 
333  ZonePtrList<Statement> statements_;
334  Scope* scope_;
335 
336  using IgnoreCompletionField = BreakableStatement::NextBitField<bool, 1>;
337  using IsBreakableField = IgnoreCompletionField::Next<bool, 1>;
338  using IsInitializationBlockForParametersField =
339  IsBreakableField::Next<bool, 1>;
340 
341  protected:
342  Block(Zone* zone, int capacity, bool ignore_completion_value,
343  bool is_breakable, bool is_initialization_block_for_parameters)
344  : BreakableStatement(kNoSourcePosition, kBlock),
345  statements_(capacity, zone),
346  scope_(nullptr) {
347  bit_field_ |= IgnoreCompletionField::encode(ignore_completion_value) |
348  IsBreakableField::encode(is_breakable) |
349  IsInitializationBlockForParametersField::encode(
350  is_initialization_block_for_parameters);
351  }
352 
353  Block(bool ignore_completion_value, bool is_breakable,
354  bool is_initialization_block_for_parameters)
355  : Block(nullptr, 0, ignore_completion_value, is_breakable,
356  is_initialization_block_for_parameters) {}
357 };

521 // Shared class for for-in and for-of statements.
522 class ForEachStatement : public IterationStatement {
523  public:
524  enum VisitMode {
525  ENUMERATE, // for (each in subject) body;
526  ITERATE // for (each of subject) body;
527  };
528 
529  using IterationStatement::Initialize;
530 
531  static const char* VisitModeString(VisitMode mode) {
532  return mode == ITERATE ? "for-of" : "for-in";
533  }
534 
535  void Initialize(Expression* each, Expression* subject, Statement* body,
536  Scope* subject_scope) {
537  IterationStatement::Initialize(body);
538  each_ = each;
539  subject_ = subject;
540  subject_scope_ = subject_scope;
541  }
542 
543  Expression* each() const { return each_; }
544  Expression* subject() const { return subject_; }
545 
546  // The parser wraps the `subject` expression into a hidden block scope
547  // in some cases. Otherwise the debugger gets confused when pausing in the
548  // `subject` expression.
549  Scope* subject_scope() const { return subject_scope_; }
550 
551  protected:
552  friend class AstNodeFactory;
553  friend Zone;
554 
555  ForEachStatement(int pos, NodeType type)
556  : IterationStatement(pos, type),
557  each_(nullptr),
558  subject_(nullptr),
559  subject_scope_(nullptr) {}
560 
561  Expression* each_;
562  Expression* subject_;
563  Scope* subject_scope_;
564 };

740 // If-statements always have non-null references to their then- and
741 // else-parts. When parsing if-statements with no explicit else-part,
742 // the parser implicitly creates an empty statement. Use the
743 // HasThenStatement() and HasElseStatement() functions to check if a
744 // given if-statement has a then- or an else-part containing code.
745 class IfStatement final : public Statement {
746  public:
747  bool HasThenStatement() const { return !then_statement_->IsEmptyStatement(); }
748  bool HasElseStatement() const { return !else_statement_->IsEmptyStatement(); }
749 
750  Expression* condition() const { return condition_; }
751  Statement* then_statement() const { return then_statement_; }
752  Statement* else_statement() const { return else_statement_; }
753 
754  void set_then_statement(Statement* s) { then_statement_ = s; }
755  void set_else_statement(Statement* s) { else_statement_ = s; }
756 
757  private:
758  friend class AstNodeFactory;
759  friend Zone;
760 
761  IfStatement(Expression* condition, Statement* then_statement,
762  Statement* else_statement, int pos)
763  : Statement(pos, kIfStatement),
764  condition_(condition),
765  then_statement_(then_statement),
766  else_statement_(else_statement) {}
767 
768  Expression* condition_;
769  Statement* then_statement_;
770  Statement* else_statement_;
771 };

788 class TryCatchStatement final : public TryStatement {
789  public:
790  Scope* scope() { return scope_; }
791  Block* catch_block() const { return catch_block_; }
792  void set_catch_block(Block* b) { catch_block_ = b; }
793 
794  // Prediction of whether exceptions thrown into the handler for this try block
795  // will be caught.
796  //
797  // BytecodeGenerator tracks the state of catch prediction, which can change
798  // with each TryCatchStatement encountered. The tracked catch prediction is
799  // later compiled into the code's handler table. The runtime uses this
800  // information to implement a feature that notifies the debugger when an
801  // uncaught exception is thrown, _before_ the exception propagates to the top.
802  //
803  // If this try/catch statement is meant to rethrow (HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT),
804  // the catch prediction value is set to the same value as the surrounding
805  // catch prediction.
806  //
807  // Since it's generally undecidable whether an exception will be caught, our
808  // prediction is only an approximation.
809  // ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
810  inline HandlerTable::CatchPrediction GetCatchPrediction(
811  HandlerTable::CatchPrediction outer_catch_prediction) const {
812  if (catch_prediction_ == HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT) {
813  return outer_catch_prediction;
814  }
815  return catch_prediction_;
816  }
817 
818  // Indicates whether or not code should be generated to clear the pending
819  // exception. The exception is cleared for cases where the exception
820  // is not guaranteed to be rethrown, indicated by the value
821  // HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT. If both the current and surrounding catch handler's
822  // are predicted uncaught, the exception is not cleared.
823  //
824  // If this handler is not going to simply rethrow the exception, this method
825  // indicates that the isolate's exception message should be cleared
826  // before executing the catch_block.
827  // In the normal use case, this flag is always on because the message object
828  // is not needed anymore when entering the catch block and should not be
829  // kept alive.
830  // The use case where the flag is off is when the catch block is guaranteed
831  // to rethrow the caught exception (using %ReThrow), which reuses the
832  // pending message instead of generating a new one.
833  // (When the catch block doesn't rethrow but is guaranteed to perform an
834  // ordinary throw, not clearing the old message is safe but not very
835  // useful.)
836  //
837  // For scripts in repl mode there is exactly one catch block with
838  // UNCAUGHT_ASYNC_AWAIT prediction. This catch block needs to preserve
839  // the exception so it can be reused later by the inspector.
840  inline bool ShouldClearException(
841  HandlerTable::CatchPrediction outer_catch_prediction) const {
842  if (catch_prediction_ == HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT_ASYNC_AWAIT) {
843  DCHECK_EQ(outer_catch_prediction, HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT);
844  return false;
845  }
846 
847  return catch_prediction_ != HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT ||
848  outer_catch_prediction != HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT;
849  }
850 
851  bool is_try_catch_for_async() {
852  return catch_prediction_ == HandlerTable::ASYNC_AWAIT;
853  }
854 
855  private:
856  friend class AstNodeFactory;
857  friend Zone;
858 
859  TryCatchStatement(Block* try_block, Scope* scope, Block* catch_block,
860  HandlerTable::CatchPrediction catch_prediction, int pos)
861  : TryStatement(try_block, pos, kTryCatchStatement),
862  scope_(scope),
863  catch_block_(catch_block),
864  catch_prediction_(catch_prediction) {}
865 
866  Scope* scope_;
867  Block* catch_block_;
868  HandlerTable::CatchPrediction catch_prediction_;
869 };

1133 // Base class for build literal boilerplate, providing common code for handling
1134 // nested subliterals.
1135 class LiteralBoilerplateBuilder {
1136  public:
1137  enum DepthKind { kUninitialized, kShallow, kNotShallow };
1138 
1139  static constexpr int kDepthKindBits = 2;
1140  static_assert((1 << kDepthKindBits) > kNotShallow);
1141 
1142  bool is_initialized() const {
1143  return kUninitialized != DepthField::decode(bit_field_);
1144  }
1145  DepthKind depth() const {
1146  DCHECK(is_initialized());
1147  return DepthField::decode(bit_field_);
1148  }
1149 
1150  // If the expression is a literal, return the literal value;
1151  // if the expression is a materialized literal and is_simple
1152  // then return an Array or Object Boilerplate Description
1153  // Otherwise, return undefined literal as the placeholder
1154  // in the object literal boilerplate.
1155  template <typename IsolateT>
1156  static DirectHandle<Object> GetBoilerplateValue(Expression* expression,
1157  IsolateT* isolate);
1158 
1159  bool is_shallow() const { return depth() == kShallow; }
1160  bool needs_initial_allocation_site() const {
1161  return NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::decode(bit_field_);
1162  }
1163 
1164  int ComputeFlags(bool disable_mementos = false) const {
1165  int flags = AggregateLiteral::kNoFlags;
1166  if (is_shallow()) flags |= AggregateLiteral::kIsShallow;
1167  if (disable_mementos) flags |= AggregateLiteral::kDisableMementos;
1168  if (needs_initial_allocation_site())
1169  flags |= AggregateLiteral::kNeedsInitialAllocationSite;
1170  return flags;
1171  }
1172 
1173  // An AggregateLiteral is simple if the values consist of only
1174  // constants and simple object and array literals.
1175  bool is_simple() const { return IsSimpleField::decode(bit_field_); }
1176 
1177  ElementsKind boilerplate_descriptor_kind() const {
1178  return BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::decode(bit_field_);
1179  }
1180 
1181  private:
1182  // we actually only care three conditions for depth
1183  // - depth == kUninitialized, DCHECK(!is_initialized())
1184  // - depth == kShallow, which means depth = 1
1185  // - depth == kNotShallow, which means depth > 1
1186  using DepthField = base::BitField<DepthKind, 0, kDepthKindBits>;
1187  using NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField = DepthField::Next<bool, 1>;
1188  using IsSimpleField = NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::Next<bool, 1>;
1189  using BoilerplateDescriptorKindField =
1190  IsSimpleField::Next<ElementsKind, kFastElementsKindBits>;
1191 
1192  protected:
1193  uint32_t bit_field_;
1194 
1195  LiteralBoilerplateBuilder() {
1196  bit_field_ =
1197  DepthField::encode(kUninitialized) |
1198  NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::encode(false) |
1199  IsSimpleField::encode(false) |
1200  BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::encode(FIRST_FAST_ELEMENTS_KIND);
1201  }
1202 
1203  void set_is_simple(bool is_simple) {
1204  bit_field_ = IsSimpleField::update(bit_field_, is_simple);
1205  }
1206 
1207  void set_boilerplate_descriptor_kind(ElementsKind kind) {
1208  DCHECK(IsFastElementsKind(kind));
1209  bit_field_ = BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::update(bit_field_, kind);
1210  }
1211 
1212  void set_depth(DepthKind depth) {
1213  DCHECK(!is_initialized());
1214  bit_field_ = DepthField::update(bit_field_, depth);
1215  }
1216 
1217  void set_needs_initial_allocation_site(bool required) {
1218  bit_field_ = NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::update(bit_field_, required);
1219  }
1220 
1221  // Populate the depth field and any flags the literal builder has
1222  static void InitDepthAndFlags(MaterializedLiteral* expr);
1223 
1224  // Populate the constant properties/elements fixed array.
1225  template <typename IsolateT>
1226  void BuildConstants(IsolateT* isolate, MaterializedLiteral* expr);
1227 
1228  template <class T, int size>
1229  using NextBitField = BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::Next<T, size>;
1230 };

1572  // Provides filtered access to the unresolved variable proxy threaded list.
1573  struct UnresolvedNext {

1575  VariableProxy** n = t;
1576  // Skip over possibly removed values.
1577  while (*n != nullptr && (*n)->is_removed_from_unresolved()) {
1578  n = (*n)->next();

1580  return n;
1581  }

1584

1642 // Assignments to a property will use one of several types of property access.
1643 // Otherwise, the assignment is to a non-property (a global, a local slot, a
1644 // parameter slot, or a destructuring pattern).
1645 enum AssignType {
1646  NON_PROPERTY, // destructuring
1647  NAMED_PROPERTY, // obj.key
1648  KEYED_PROPERTY, // obj[key] and obj.#key when #key is a private field
1649  NAMED_SUPER_PROPERTY, // super.key
1650  KEYED_SUPER_PROPERTY, // super[key]
1651  PRIVATE_METHOD, // obj.#key: #key is a private method
1652  PRIVATE_GETTER_ONLY, // obj.#key: #key only has a getter defined
1653  PRIVATE_SETTER_ONLY, // obj.#key: #key only has a setter defined
1654  PRIVATE_GETTER_AND_SETTER, // obj.#key: #key has both accessors defined
1655  PRIVATE_DEBUG_DYNAMIC, // obj.#key: #key is private that requires dynamic
1656  // lookup in debug-evaluate.
1657 };

1659 class Property final : public Expression {
1660  public:
1661  bool is_optional_chain_link() const {
1662  return IsOptionalChainLinkField::decode(bit_field_);
1663  }
1664 
1665  bool IsValidReferenceExpression() const { return true; }
1666 
1667  Expression* obj() const { return obj_; }
1668  Expression* key() const { return key_; }
1669 
1670  bool IsSuperAccess() { return obj()->IsSuperPropertyReference(); }
1671  bool IsPrivateReference() const { return key()->IsPrivateName(); }
1672 
1673  // Returns the properties assign type.
1674  static AssignType GetAssignType(Property* property) {
1675  if (property == nullptr) return NON_PROPERTY;
1676  if (property->IsPrivateReference()) {
1677  DCHECK(!property->IsSuperAccess());
1678  VariableProxy* proxy = property->key()->AsVariableProxy();
1679  DCHECK_NOT_NULL(proxy);
1680  Variable* var = proxy->var();
1681 
1682  switch (var->mode()) {
1683  case VariableMode::kPrivateMethod:
1684  return PRIVATE_METHOD;
1685  case VariableMode::kConst:
1686  return KEYED_PROPERTY; // Use KEYED_PROPERTY for private fields.
1687  case VariableMode::kPrivateGetterOnly:
1688  return PRIVATE_GETTER_ONLY;
1689  case VariableMode::kPrivateSetterOnly:
1690  return PRIVATE_SETTER_ONLY;
1691  case VariableMode::kPrivateGetterAndSetter:
1692  return PRIVATE_GETTER_AND_SETTER;
1693  case VariableMode::kDynamic:
1694  // From debug-evaluate.
1695  return PRIVATE_DEBUG_DYNAMIC;
1696  default:
1697  UNREACHABLE();
1698  }
1699  }
1700  bool super_access = property->IsSuperAccess();
1701  return (property->key()->IsPropertyName())
1702  ? (super_access ? NAMED_SUPER_PROPERTY : NAMED_PROPERTY)
1703  : (super_access ? KEYED_SUPER_PROPERTY : KEYED_PROPERTY);
1704  }
1705 
1706  private:
1707  friend class AstNodeFactory;
1708  friend Zone;
1709 
1710  Property(Expression* obj, Expression* key, int pos, bool optional_chain)
1711  : Expression(pos, kProperty), obj_(obj), key_(key) {
1712  bit_field_ |= IsOptionalChainLinkField::encode(optional_chain);
1713  }
1714 
1715  using IsOptionalChainLinkField = Expression::NextBitField<bool, 1>;
1716 
1717  Expression* obj_;
1718  Expression* key_;
1719 };

2103  }
2104 
2105  // Conditional Chain Expression stores the conditional chain entries out of
2106  // line, along with their operation's position. The else expression is stored
2107  // inline. This Expression is reserved for ternary operations that have more
2108  // than one conditional chain entry. For ternary operations with only one
2109  // conditional chain entry, the Conditional Expression is used instead.
2110  //
2111  // So an conditional chain:
2112  //
2113  // cond ? then : cond ? then : cond ? then : else
2114  //
2115  // is stored as:
2116  //
2117  // [(cond, then), (cond, then),...] else
2118  // '-----------------------------' '----'
2119  // conditional chain entries else
2120  //
2121  // Example:
2122  //
2123  // Expression: v1 == 1 ? "a" : v2 == 2 ? "b" : "c"
2124  //
2125  // conditionat_chain_entries_: [(v1 == 1, "a", 0), (v2 == 2, "b", 14)]
2126  // else_expression_: "c"
2127  //
2128  // Example of a _not_ expected expression (only one chain entry):
2129  //
2130  // Expression: v1 == 1 ? "a" : "b"
2131  //
2132 
2133  struct ConditionalChainEntry {
2134  Expression* condition;
2135  Expression* then_expression;
2136  int condition_position;
2137  ConditionalChainEntry(Expression* cond, Expression* then, int pos)
2138  : condition(cond), then_expression(then), condition_position(pos) {}
2139  };
2140  ZoneVector<ConditionalChainEntry> conditional_chain_entries_;
2141  Expression* else_expression_;
2142 };

2215 // There are several types of Suspend node:
2216 //
2217 // Yield
2218 // YieldStar
2219 // Await
2220 //
2221 // Our Yield is different from the JS yield in that it "returns" its argument as
2222 // is, without wrapping it in an iterator result object. Such wrapping, if
2223 // desired, must be done beforehand (see the parser).
2224 class Suspend : public Expression {
2225  public:
2226  // With {kNoControl}, the {Suspend} behaves like yield, except that it never
2227  // throws and never causes the current generator to return. This is used to
2228  // desugar yield*.
2229  // TODO(caitp): remove once yield* desugaring for async generators is handled
2230  // in BytecodeGenerator.
2231  enum OnAbruptResume { kOnExceptionThrow, kNoControl };
2232 
2233  Expression* expression() const { return expression_; }
2234  OnAbruptResume on_abrupt_resume() const {
2235  return OnAbruptResumeField::decode(bit_field_);
2236  }
2237 
2238  private:
2239  friend class AstNodeFactory;
2240  friend Zone;
2241  friend class Yield;
2242  friend class YieldStar;
2243  friend class Await;
2244 
2245  Suspend(NodeType node_type, Expression* expression, int pos,
2246  OnAbruptResume on_abrupt_resume)
2247  : Expression(pos, node_type), expression_(expression) {
2248  bit_field_ |= OnAbruptResumeField::encode(on_abrupt_resume);
2249  }
2250 
2251  Expression* expression_;
2252 
2253  using OnAbruptResumeField = Expression::NextBitField<OnAbruptResume, 1>;
2254 };

2927 // ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2928 // Basic visitor
2929 // Sub-class should parametrize AstVisitor with itself, e.g.:
2930 // class SpecificVisitor : public AstVisitor<SpecificVisitor> { ... }
2931 
2932 template <class Subclass>
2933 class AstVisitor {
2934  public:
2935  void Visit(AstNode* node) { impl()->Visit(node); }
2936 
2937  void VisitDeclarations(Declaration::List* declarations) {
2938  for (Declaration* decl : *declarations) Visit(decl);
2939  }
2940 
2941  void VisitStatements(const ZonePtrList<Statement>* statements) {
2942  for (int i = 0; i < statements->length(); i++) {
2943  Statement* stmt = statements->at(i);
2944  Visit(stmt);
2945  }
2946  }
2947 
2948  void VisitExpressions(const ZonePtrList<Expression>* expressions) {
2949  for (int i = 0; i < expressions->length(); i++) {
2950  // The variable statement visiting code may pass null expressions
2951  // to this code. Maybe this should be handled by introducing an
2952  // undefined expression or literal? Revisit this code if this
2953  // changes.
2954  Expression* expression = expressions->at(i);
2955  if (expression != nullptr) Visit(expression);
2956  }
2957  }
2958 
2959  protected:
2960  Subclass* impl() { return static_cast<Subclass*>(this); }
2961 };
2962 
2963 #define GENERATE_VISIT_CASE(NodeType) \
2964  case AstNode::k##NodeType: \
2965  return this->impl()->Visit##NodeType(static_cast<NodeType*>(node));
2966 
2967 #define GENERATE_FAILURE_CASE(NodeType) \
2968  case AstNode::k##NodeType: \
2969  UNREACHABLE();
2970 
2971 #define GENERATE_AST_VISITOR_SWITCH() \
2972  switch (node->node_type()) { \
2973  AST_NODE_LIST(GENERATE_VISIT_CASE) \
2974  FAILURE_NODE_LIST(GENERATE_FAILURE_CASE) \
2975  }
2976 
2977 #define DEFINE_AST_VISITOR_SUBCLASS_MEMBERS() \
2978  public: \
2979  void VisitNoStackOverflowCheck(AstNode* node) { \
2980  GENERATE_AST_VISITOR_SWITCH() \
2981  } \
2982  \
2983  void Visit(AstNode* node) { \
2984  if (CheckStackOverflow()) return; \
2985  VisitNoStackOverflowCheck(node); \
2986  } \
2987  \
2988  void SetStackOverflow() { stack_overflow_ = true; } \
2989  void ClearStackOverflow() { stack_overflow_ = false; } \
2990  bool HasStackOverflow() const { return stack_overflow_; } \
2991  \
2992  bool CheckStackOverflow() { \
2993  if (stack_overflow_) return true; \
2994  if (GetCurrentStackPosition() < stack_limit_) { \
2995  stack_overflow_ = true; \
2996  return true; \
2997  } \
2998  return false; \
2999  } \
3000  \
3001  protected: \
3002  uintptr_t stack_limit() const { return stack_limit_; } \
3003  \

3006  stack_limit_ = isolate->stack_guard()->real_climit(); \
3007  stack_overflow_ = false; \

3415  Assignment* NewAssignment(Token::Value op,
3416  Expression* target,
3417  Expression* value,
3418  int pos) {
3419  DCHECK(Token::IsAssignmentOp(op));
3420  DCHECK_NOT_NULL(target);
3421  DCHECK_NOT_NULL(value);
3422 
3423  if (op != Token::kInit && target->IsVariableProxy()) {
3424  target->AsVariableProxy()->set_is_assigned();
3425  }
